citations:
    citation-affc-jaime-i:
        source: source-affc
        properties:
            locator: "Jaime I"
            text_from_source: "I commanded the eunuch to take him to a ship, not to your bedchamber. The blood is on his hands as much as . . . as Tyrion's."
            accessed: "2026-03-06"
        notes: "POV: Jaime Lannister. Jaime stands vigil over Tywin's body in the Great Sept of Baelor, kept company by Ser Balon Swann and Ser Loras Tyrell. In an extended internal monologue, Jaime reveals he was the one who helped Tyrion escape: he cornered Varys with a dagger and compelled him to free Tyrion, intending to put him on a ship. He did not intend for Tyrion to kill Tywin. Jaime feels responsibility for his father's death. He reflects on his history as a knight: his service to Aerys II, the Kingsguard's failure to protect the prince during the Defiance of Duskendale, the Battle of the Bells, and the sack of King's Landing. He meets with the White Book of the Kingsguard and writes his own meager entry. Cersei visits and Jaime refuses her seduction — he tells her he is done with her, a decisive break. Key figures mentioned: Ser Balon Swann, Ser Loras Tyrell (offering to stand vigil), Cersei. Jaime's private confession about freeing Tyrion. The White Book of the Kingsguard described."
